redis/redis#12485.body:
**The problem/use-case that the feature addresses**

If the data (value of key) changes during a round-trip to the user interface and back, we need a way to detect this situation in order to avoid dataloss in situations when there are multiple users editing data on same keys.

**Description of the feature**

Prevent changes to the data when another user has already changed the data behind the scenes.
Implementation as CAS token.

If CAS token does not match current token, then set must fail.
If CAS token matches, then set to given value and create new cas token


First part: Get CAS token

SET hello "Hello, World!"

GET hello CAS
"Hello, World!" 
"37eaa6435955b815" 

Alternatively:
GETCAS hello
"37eaa6435955b815"

Second part:

SET hello "Hello, You!" CAS "37eaa6435955b815"

If the previous data is still "Hello, World!" this key 'hello' should be set to "Hello, You!", because the CAS token has not changed.
However, if another user has meanwhile changed the data into "Hello, Me!" and thereby changed its CAS token into "37eaa6434791eb9b" then the SET should fail. 

In the given example above the tokens have been calculated with simple hashing as follows:

uint64_t simpleCasToken(const uint8_t* data, size_t length) {
    uint64_t token = 0;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < length; i++) {
        token = token * 31 + data[i];
    }
    return token;
}

void CasTokenToString(uint64_t token, char* buffer) {
    sprintf(buffer, "%llx", token);
}

uint64_t stringToCasToken(const char* buffer) {
    uint64_t token;
    sscanf(buffer, "%llx", &token);
    return token;
}

In Redis code there are already tested functions to do similar hashing (such as siphash), which could be used instead. 

This functionality would fit with the NX/XX/LT/GT type of "Only Set If Condition" (OSIC) -features.


**Alternatives you've considered**

Client code can implement this feature by themselves, but this is not atomic and can still happen. 
WATCH, MULTI, EXEC can be used to create limited CAS functionality, but using it in a web environment, or in situations when the connections may disconnect, can be very tricky.

**Additional information**

Relates to #12454 #8361 #5917

Regarding key types that have multiple fields or items, maybe this discussion about inner workings ja Java hashcode may come in handy: https://www.baeldung.com/java-hashcode

redis/redis#13885.body:
cilentsCron:

        if (clientsCronHandleTimeout(c,now)) continue;
        if (clientsCronResizeQueryBuffer(c)) continue;
        if (clientsCronFreeArgvIfIdle(c)) continue;
        if (clientsCronResizeOutputBuffer(c,now)) continue;

        if (clientsCronTrackExpansiveClients(c, curr_peak_mem_usage_slot)) continue;

Currently, Redis handles client-related tasks such as timeout checks, buffer resizing, and memory management within the main thread. While this design ensures efficiency and simplicity, it may lead to the main thread waiting for IO threads to pause, potentially impacting performance in certain scenarios.

I suggest moving these client handling tasks to IO threads. This approach could offer several advantages:

1. Simplified Main Thread: Reducing the load on the main thread by offloading non-critical, non-real-time tasks to IO threads could streamline its operations.
2. Enhanced Performance: By distributing tasks across IO threads, we might achieve better utilization of system resources and reduce potential bottlenecks.
3. Easier Implementation: Handling client-related tasks in IO threads could simplify the implementation by avoiding complex synchronization between the main thread and IO operations.

redis/redis#14358.body:
Variable *histogram->total_count with floating-point type whose possible value set allows a zero value at redis-benchmark.c:953 by calling function 'hdr_init' is passed to function at redis-benchmark.c:975, where it is used as a denominator at redis-benchmark.c:837 by calling function 'hdr_mean'. The result of division is further used without a check for NaN, which leads to undefined program behavior

```c
showLatencyReport();
``` 
https://github.com/redis/redis/blob/8.0.3/src/redis-benchmark.c#L975

Description hdr_mean

```c
 while (hdr_iter_next(&iter))
    {
        if (0 != iter.count)
        {
            total += iter.count * hdr_median_equivalent_value(h, iter.value);
        }
    }

    return (total * 1.0) / h->total_count;
``` 

https://github.com/redis/redis/blob/8.0.3/deps/hdr_histogram/hdr_histogram.c#L749

During normal operation, the variable h->total_count will definitely be different from 0, but if a network problem occurs with sending requests to a Redis server that measures response time, or, for example, this server stops responding, then h->total_count may become equal to 0, which will lead to undefined program behavior.

It is recommended to include a check for 0 in the code.

Found by Linux Verification Center ( linuxtesting.org ) with SVACE
Reporter: Gushchin Egor ( guschin058@yandex.ru)

redis/redis#14626.body:
**Describe the bug**

The `hnsw_cursor_free()` function has a use-after-free bug where it accesses `cursor->index` after the cursor has been freed with `hfree(cursor)`.

In `hnsw_cursor_free()` at line ~2584, the code frees the cursor and then tries to access it:

```c
void hnsw_cursor_free(hnswCursor *cursor) {
    if (pthread_rwlock_wrlock(&cursor->index->global_lock) != 0) {
        return;
    }

    hnswCursor *x = cursor->index->cursors;
    hnswCursor *prev = NULL;
    while(x) {
        if (x == cursor) {
            if (prev)
                prev->next = cursor->next;
            else
                cursor->index->cursors = cursor->next;
            hfree(cursor);  // <-- cursor is freed here
            break;
        }
        prev = x;
        x = x->next;
    }
    pthread_rwlock_unlock(&cursor->index->global_lock);  // <-- BUG: accessing freed memory
}
```

redis/redis#14677.body:
**Describe the bug**

Redis core triggers a **heap-use-after-free (UAF)** in the Modules API path `RedisModule_UnblockClient()` (`RM_UnblockClient` in `src/module.c`) when a module keeps a `RedisModuleBlockedClient *` handle and later calls `RedisModule_UnblockClient(bc, ...)` from a background thread **after the client disconnected and the main thread already freed `bc`**.

This manifests as a server crash (DoS) under AddressSanitizer, and is undefined behavior in non-sanitized builds.

Key points:
- Affected API: `RedisModule_UnblockClient(RedisModuleBlockedClient *bc, void *privdata)`
- Affected core code: `RM_UnblockClient()` / `moduleUnblockClientByHandle()` / `moduleHandleBlockedClients()`
- Trigger condition: module blocks a client (e.g., `RedisModule_BlockClientOnKeys`), client disconnects, module thread later unblocks using a stale `bc`.

**To reproduce**

This report assumes you have:
- a Redis source checkout (or your Redis repo) at `<REDIS_SRC>`

Reproduction uses a real TCP client that sends a module command and then disconnects immediately.

1) Build Redis with ASan (tested on `unstable`):

```bash
cd <REDIS_SRC>
make -j"$(nproc)" SANITIZER=address
```

2) Create a minimal reproducer module (save as `repro_module.c` next to your Redis checkout, or anywhere convenient):

```c
#include "redismodule.h"
#include <pthread.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

/* Dummy timeout callback required by RM_UnblockClient when blocked_on_keys=1. */
static int DummyTimeout(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, RedisModuleString **argv, int argc) {
    REDISMODULE_NOT_USED(argv);
    REDISMODULE_NOT_USED(argc);
    RedisModule_ReplyWithNull(ctx);
    return REDISMODULE_OK;
}

static void *RaceThread(void *arg) {
    RedisModuleBlockedClient *bc = (RedisModuleBlockedClient *)arg;
    fprintf(stderr, "Thread starting for bc %p\n", bc);
    /* Give time for: client disconnect -> main thread cleanup -> bc freed. */
    usleep(200 * 1000); /* 200ms */
    fprintf(stderr, "Thread calling UnblockClient for bc %p\n", bc);
    RedisModule_UnblockClient(bc, NULL); /* UAF: bc may already be freed */
    return NULL;
}

static int RaceCommand(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, RedisModuleString **argv, int argc) {
    if (argc != 2) return RedisModule_WrongArity(ctx);
    RedisModuleString *key = argv[1];

    /* Block the client on keys, obtain bc handle. */
    RedisModuleBlockedClient *bc =
        RedisModule_BlockClientOnKeys(ctx, NULL, DummyTimeout, NULL, 0, &key, 1, NULL);

    pthread_t tid;
    int err = pthread_create(&tid, NULL, RaceThread, bc);
    if (err != 0) {
        char buf[128];
        snprintf(buf, sizeof(buf), "pthread_create failed: %s", strerror(err));
        return RedisModule_ReplyWithError(ctx, buf);
    }
    pthread_detach(tid);
    return REDISMODULE_OK;
}

int RedisModule_OnLoad(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, RedisModuleString **argv, int argc) {
    REDISMODULE_NOT_USED(argv);
    REDISMODULE_NOT_USED(argc);
    if (RedisModule_Init(ctx, "race", 1, REDISMODULE_APIVER_1) == REDISMODULE_ERR)
        return REDISMODULE_ERR;
    if (RedisModule_CreateCommand(ctx, "race.trigger", RaceCommand, "write", 1, 1, 1) ==
        REDISMODULE_ERR)
        return REDISMODULE_ERR;
    return REDISMODULE_OK;
}
```

3) Compile the module (ensure it can include `<REDIS_SRC>/src/redismodule.h`):

```bash
gcc -fPIC -shared -o repro_module.so repro_module.c -I "<REDIS_SRC>/src" -lpthread
```

4) Start `redis-server` with ASan build and load the module:

```bash
"<REDIS_SRC>/src/redis-server" --daemonize no --protected-mode no --loadmodule "$(pwd)/repro_module.so" 2>redis.log
```

5) In a separate terminal, run a minimal raw-socket client that sends the command and disconnects immediately.
Save as `repro_client.py`:

```python
import socket
import time

def main():
    s = socket.socket(socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_STREAM)
    s.connect(("127.0.0.1", 6379))
    # RESP: race.trigger foo
    s.sendall(b"*2\r\n$12\r\nrace.trigger\r\n$3\r\nfoo\r\n")
    # Short delay to increase likelihood the command has blocked.
    time.sleep(0.00005)
    s.close()

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
```

Run it multiple times (the module spawns a background thread per call):

```bash
python3 repro_client.py
python3 repro_client.py
python3 repro_client.py
```

What the reproducer does (minimal behavior):
- Module command `race.trigger <key>` calls `RedisModule_BlockClientOnKeys(...)` and gets a `RedisModuleBlockedClient *bc`.
- Module spawns a `pthread` that sleeps briefly and then calls `RedisModule_UnblockClient(bc, NULL)`.
- Client disconnects immediately after sending the command (raw socket `close()`).
- Main thread processes blocked clients and frees `bc`.
- Background thread later dereferences `bc` inside `RM_UnblockClient()` → UAF.

6) Inspect server stderr / `redis.log` for the ASan report:

```bash
grep -n "ERROR: AddressSanitizer: heap-use-after-free\\|SUMMARY: AddressSanitizer" -n redis.log
```

**Expected behavior**

Redis should **not dereference a freed `RedisModuleBlockedClient *`** even if a module calls `RedisModule_UnblockClient()` after the client disconnect cleanup path ran.

Possible acceptable outcomes (depending on intended API contract):
- Return an error (e.g., `REDISMODULE_ERR`) when `bc` is stale/invalid, without crashing.
- Make stale handles fail safely (e.g., generation/validity check), rather than use-after-free.

**Additional information**

- Tested Redis:
  - Branch: `unstable`
  - Commit: `16068d6b6312bdd6c191afbed703b2296df4909b`
  - Build: `SANITIZER=address`
- Repro artifacts:
  - Provided inline in this report as `repro_module.c` and `repro_client.py` (copy/paste).

ASan evidence (single report includes alloc/free/use chain):
- **Use**: `RM_UnblockClient` (`src/module.c:8507`) from module thread
- **Free**: `moduleHandleBlockedClients` (`src/module.c:8649`) in main thread
- **Alloc**: `moduleBlockClient` (`src/module.c:8033`) in main thread

Note on triggerability / threat model:
- Loading a module is typically an admin action, but once such a module is loaded, **an unprivileged client can trigger the crash** by executing the module command and disconnecting immediately.
- Non-ASan builds may not crash reliably (still UB); ASan makes the bug deterministic and provides proof.

redis/redis#14864.body:
**Describe the bug**

`lpBatchInsert()` may leak the temporary encoded-entry buffer `enc` when the function exits through certain early return paths.

**To reproduce**

Inside `lpBatchInsert()`, the function conditionally allocates a temporary array of encoded entries (lines **1167–1170**):
``` c
if (len > sizeof(tmp) / sizeof(struct listpackInsertEntry)) {
    /* If 'len' is larger than the local buffer size, allocate on the heap. */
    enc = zmalloc(len * sizeof(struct listpackInsertEntry));
}
```
Later in the function, there are early return paths that occur after this allocation.

1. The first occurs when the computed size of the new listpack exceeds the allowed limit (line **1211**):
    ``` c
    if (new_listpack_bytes > UINT32_MAX) return NULL;
    ```

    If `enc` was allocated on the heap (i.e., `enc != tmp`), returning directly here causes the allocated buffer to be leaked.

2. A second early return exists in the reallocation path (lines **1218–1223**):
    ``` c
    /* Realloc before: we need more room. */
    if (new_listpack_bytes > old_listpack_bytes &&
        new_listpack_bytes > lp_malloc_size(lp)) {
        if ((lp = lp_realloc(lp,new_listpack_bytes)) == NULL) return NULL;
        dst = lp + poff;
    }
    ```

    If `lp_realloc()` fails, the function returns `NULL` without releasing `enc`, which again results in a memory leak.


**Expected behavior**

The temporary buffer `enc` should be released on all exit paths after it may have been heap-allocated.

redis/redis#14879.body:
## PERSIST/KEEPTTL
PERSIST can only be given for HGETEX and KEEPTTL for HSETEX but the code doesn’t verify it in case of error:
```
127.0.0.1:5555> HSETEX h ex 100 persist fields 1 k v
(error) ERR Only one of EX, PX, EXAT, PXAT or KEEPTTL arguments can be specified
```
i think it will be more readable if you used this structure:
```
        } else if (command_type == HASH_CMD_HGETEX && !strcasecmp(c->argv[i]->ptr, "PERSIST")) {
            if (*flags & (HFE_EX | HFE_EXAT | HFE_PX | HFE_PXAT | HFE_PERSIST))
                goto err_expiration;
            *flags |= HFE_PERSIST;
        }
```
instead of this block:
```
    /* Validate command-specific argument compatibility */
    if ((command_type == HASH_CMD_HGETEX && (*flags & (HFE_KEEPTTL | HFE_FXX | HFE_FNX))) ||
        (command_type == HASH_CMD_HSETEX && (*flags & HFE_PERSIST))) {
        addReplyError(c, "unknown argument");
        return C_ERR;
    }
```
that would also solve the problem (error will be “unknown argument” in case of HSETEX + PERSIST)

## existence of FIELDS
this is only a potential bug, but worth solving: parseHashFieldExpireArgs doesn’t fail in case the mandatory FIELDS was not given
currently we are guarded by the argc check, but if we had more optional args like EX, FNX etc that weren’t mutually exclusive we could reach this situation

## multiple FIELDS
```
127.0.0.1:5555> HSETEX key FIELDS 1 f1 v1 FIELDS 1 f2 v2
(integer) 1
127.0.0.1:5555> hgetall key
1) "f2"
2) "v2"
```
